the reality: the problem of the twenty-first century is still the problem of the color line. In Race Still Matters, contributors drawn from a wide array of disciplines use multidisciplinary methods to explore topics such as Black family experiences, hate crimes, race and popular culture, residual discrimination, economic and occupational opportunity gaps, healthcare disparities, education, law enforcement issues, youth culture, and the depiction of Black female athletes. The volume offers irrefutable evidence that race still very much matters in the United States today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAfrican AmericansxRace identity. 0aAfrican AmericansxSocial conditionsx21st century. 0aAfrican AmericansxSocial conditionsy21st century. 0aRace discriminationxUnited States. 0aRace discriminationzUnited States. 0aRacismxUnited States. 0aRacismzUnited States. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aAmerican Studies : American Culture. 4aHistory : American History. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Sociology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh1 aBalogun, Emmanuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrackett, LaToya T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrunson, Rod K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Daniel R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aD’Souza, Amanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGomer, Justin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGosa, Travis L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelley, Samantha S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKiuchi, Yuya, eeditor